text: New Strategies in the Eﬃcient Total Syntheses of Polycyclic Natural Products Published as part of the Accounts of Chemical Research special issue “Total Synthesis of Natural Products”. and Xiaoguang Lei* Weilong Liu,

CONSPECTUS: Polycyclic natural products are an inexhaustible source of medicinal agents, and their complex molecular architecture renders challenging synthetic targets where innovative and eﬀective approaches for their rapid construction are urgently required. The total synthesis of polycyclic natural products has witnessed exponential progression along with the emergence of new synthetic strategies and concepts, such as sequential C−H functionalizations, radical-based transformations, and functional group pairing strategies. Our group exerts continued interest in the construction of bioactive and structurally complex natural products as well as evaluation of the mode of action of these molecules. In this Account, we will showcase how these new synthetic strategies are employed and guide our total synthesis endeavors. During the last two decades, a series of remarkable advances in C−H functionalization have led to the emergence of many new approaches to directly functionalize C−H bonds into useful functional groups. These selective transformations have provided a great opportunity for the step- and atom-economical construction of key fragments in complex molecule synthesis. We recently furnished the total syntheses for polycyclic natural products: incarviatone A, chrysomycin A, polycarcin V, and gilvocarcin V by employing a multiple C−H bond functionalization strategy. The polysubstituted benzene or naphthalene skeleton was constructed through sequential and site-selective C−H functionalizations from readily available simple starting materials, which reduced the number of steps and streamlined synthesis. Recently, we have also completed the total syntheses for a number of skeletally diverse tetracyclic Isodon diterpenoids inspired by their biogenesis and radical-based retrosynthetic disconnections. Radical transformations are strategically and tactically utilized in our syntheses, and radical-based reactions, including organo-SOMO catalysis, Birch reduction, regioselective 1,6-dienyne reductive cyclization, visible-light-mediated Schenck ene reaction, and photoradical-mediated late-stage skeletal rearrangement, play signiﬁcant roles in our synthetic endeavors. Protecting-group-free and scalable syntheses are also built into our work to achieve the “ideal” synthesis. Furthermore, our synthetic work reveals that late-stage skeletal rearrangement through a photo radical process is possible in a biological setting in complement with nature’s carbocation chemistry in complex natural product biosynthesis. Lycopodium alkaloids are a large family of structurally unique polycyclic natural products with impressive biological activities. Owing to their fascinating polycyclic architectures and diverse biological activities, these alkaloids have continued to serve as targets as well as inspirations for the synthetic community for decades. To access these bioactive natural products or natural product-like molecules for biological exploration and drug discovery, we applied a novel functional group pairing strategy to furnish the total syntheses for several Lycopodium alkaloids and obtained numerous skeletally diverse compounds with structural complexity comparable to natural products.

Natural products, possessing a vast and diverse chemical space, have been historically used as active constituents in traditional medicines and currently still act as the leading choice for the discovery of novel drug candidates.5,6 The total synthesis of natural products, especially with polycyclic skeletons, has attracted long-standing interest and remains among the most exciting and dynamic areas in synthetic endeavors.7 Total synthesis, although a relatively young enterprise, does share certain similarities with architecture.8 From a thatched cottage during the slash-and-burn period to ornate modern buildings, new materials’ contributions do not go unnoticed. Similarly, along with the emergence of new strategies and concepts, total synthesis has witnessed an exponential progression. More importantly, our total synthesis acts as the driving force for the discovery of bioactive compounds as well as a deep under- standing of their mechanism of action (MOA). ■ TOTAL SYNTHESIS OF POLYSUBSTITUTED During the last two decades, the ﬁeld of C−H functionalization has grown tremendously, which has led to the emergence of an impressive number of new approaches to directly functionalize carbon−hydrogen bonds (C−H) into carbon−carbon (C−C) and carbon−heteroatom bonds (C−X).12 The C−H function- alization approach enables the synthesis of structurally complex molecules that is more step- and atom-economical compared with conventional synthesis, which always relies on manipu- lation of preprepared reactive functional groups.13

The recent rapid growth of selective C−H bond functional- ization of aromatic bonds opens the door for the construction of polysubstituted aromatic scaﬀolds by using multiple and sequential C−H functionalizations of omnipresent C−H bonds in simple aromatic starting materials.13f Owing to ubiquitous similar C−H bonds in simple aromatic cores, the challenge is the selective transformation of a speciﬁc C−H bond in a predictable manner. Another challenge is that the directing group employed in the method should be part of the target molecules or easily removed/functionalized. To control the selectivity, many C−H functionalizations often require addi- tional directing groups, increasing the complexity of the whole AROMATICS VIA SEQUENTIAL C−H FUNCTIONALIZATIONS https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00531 Acc. Furthermore, functionalization is also crucial, especially when the method is employed in the early stage. For sequential C−H functionalization of benzene and naphthalene, the ﬁrst functional group in the starting material could act as a directing group to selectively functionalize one C− H bond, then the substitutes in the aromatic ring could serve as new directing groups to functionalize other C−H bonds. Inspired by the attractive bioactivity and unique polycyclic framework, our group achieved the ﬁrst total synthesis of (−)-incarviatone A (1) using a sequential C−H functionalization strategy in 2015.2 Sarpong and co-workers reported a formal synthesis in 2020.16 We anticipated that the [2.2.2] skeleton in (−)-incarviatone A can be constructed by utilizing the biomimetic cascade strategy from 18, which can be assembled from dialdehyde 19, boronic ester 20, and phenol 21 via Suzuki coupling and phenolic aldol condensation. The tetrasubstituted indanyl dialdehyde 19 was envisaged to be accessed from simple phenylacetic acid 22 via four sequential and diﬀerent C−H functionalizations (Scheme 2).

The sequential C−H functionalization was initiated by carboxylic acid-directed ortho-C−H alkylation of 22 (Scheme 3). The desired ortho-propyl phenyl acetic acid 24 was obtained on a gram scale using the protocol of Yu et al.17 Alternatively, 24 can also be prepared on a 40 g scale from 23 in one pot. The enantioselective construction of the Indane skeleton in 26 via Rh-catalyzed intramolecular diasteroselective C−H insertion is regarded as a major challenge.18 After extensive examination, 26 was constructed in 70% yield and 93% ee (enantiomeric excess) on a 28 g scale by using (−)-borneol as a chiral auxiliary and Rh2(R-PTTL) as the catalyst. 26 was transformed to iodide 27 through a modiﬁcation of Yu’s carboxylic acid directed ortho-C− H iodination on a 7 g scale.19 Subsequent carbonylation, reduction, and protection of 27 yielded 28, which was subjected to sterically controlled, meta-selective Hartwig C−H borylation and one-pot bromination/deprotection20 to yield diol 29. Subsequent Swern oxidation delivered dialdehyde 19 in 10 steps on gram scale from 22.

Dialdehyde 19 underwent a three-step transformation to yield key precursor 18 (15-OHα/β = 1.7:1) (Scheme 4). 18 was converted to (−)-incarviatone A (1) in 46% yield along with minor isomer 32 in 19% yield in one pot. Mechanistically, both diastereoisomers of 18 were initially converted into 33 in 78% yield. 33 can be easily converted into regioisomer 34 via 15α- hydroxyl group oxa-Michael addition. Subjecting 34 to 2% NaOH in EtOH (v/v = 1:1) at −20 °C aﬀorded (−)-in- carviatone A (1) in 53% yield and its isomer 32 in 18% yield. Total Synthesis of Chrysomycin A, Polycarcin V, and Gilvocarcin V In search of naturally occurring anti-TB drugs, Zhang10 and Kumar21 independently discovered chrysomycin A (2) that shows promising anti-TB activity. Chrysomycin A, an antitumor antibiotic ﬁrst isolated from Streptomyces A-419 in 1955,22 belongs to the gilvocarcin family of C-glycosylated polyketide natural products, including gilvocarcin V (3) and polycarcin V (4). Unlike the sugar moieties linked at the ortho-position of phenol in most C-glycosylated natural products, the virenose fragment in chrysomycin A (2) is linked at the para-carbon of phenol. This uncommon para-substituted sugar moiety poses a challenge for the preparation of these para-substituted C- glycosides or analogues to fully elucidate their biological function. The Suzuki group reported the remarkable total synthesis of gilvocarcin V (3) in 1994 using early stage glycosylation.23 Recently, polycarcin V (4) was synthesized by Minehan and co-workers.24 To generate various natural product analogues for potential anti-TB activity lead compound discovery, our group recently realized a scalable synthesis of chrysomycin A and its two natural congeners polycarcin V and gilvocarcin V in 10 steps.10 This work provides a robust approach to prepare over 30 new analogues of the natural for a subsequent structure−activity relationship product investigation. https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00531 Acc. It is worth noting that C3 diversiﬁcation was achieved via a Pd- catalyzed meta-C−H functionalization strategy originally developed by Yu and co-workers.30 More than 30 structurally diverse analogues were synthesized and evaluated for anti- tuberculosis activity. pterisolic acid B shows a signiﬁcant cytoprotective eﬀect against cisplatin-induced cytotoxicity by covalently modifying cysteine- 171 of keap1 (Kelch-like ECH-associated protein 1).31a Since then, the synthesis of an assortment of biologically active ent- kauranes as well as their biological evaluations have been reported by our laboratory (Figure 1).3,4,11 The ent-kaurane diterpenoids are a large and unique family of natural products with more than 1200 members isolated, and the ﬁrst investigation dates back to 1910.32 The intriguing structures containing a bridged bicyclo[3.2.1]octane ring system as well as potential biological activities have attracted tremendous endeavors from the synthetic community over the past decades.33,34 Unlike conventional total syntheses based on two-electron transformations, radical chemistry has garnered increasing interest to sustain elegant syntheses to the frontier of synthetic chemistry due to its high practicality and chemoselectivity.35 Furthermore, radical processes are certainly not rare in natural product biosynthesis. Encouraged by our successful chemical genetic investigation of ent-kaurane as well as the broader adoption of one-electron-based transformations, we envisaged that ent-kaurane diterpenoids could be constructed by means of radical transformations. Radical-Based Strategy for ent-Kaurane Diterpenoid Synthesis is widely accepted that ent-kaurane diterpenoids are It biosynthetically derived from a common intermediate ent- pimarenyl cation (62) upon a series of enzymatic cyclizations starting from geranylgeranyl diphosphate (61, GGPP). Sub- sequent successive carbocationic cyclization rearrangements generate various types of diterpenoid skeletons, including ent- kauranes.36 Of note, enzymatic carbocationic rearrangements have been proposed as being responsible for skeletal rearrange- ments of ent-kaurane diterpenoids into jungermannenone diterpenoids (Scheme 8a).37 https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00531 Acc. Radical-Based Strategy for Diterpenoid Synthesis Much inspired by the aforementioned biosynthetic hypoth- esis, our synthesis follows the same sequence from tricycles to tetracyclic ent-kaurane diterpenoids. As shown in Scheme 8c, our synthesis commenced with the construction of tricycle 70 from commercially available starting materials. Several two- electron-based enantioselective polyene cyclization strategies turned out to be unsuccessful, and radical-based MacMillan SOMO catalysis38 was proven to be most eﬃcient. Sub- sequently, under Birch reduction conditions, a reductive cascade gave rise to dienone 71, which was sequentially transformed into dienyne 65a and 65b as remarkable radical carriers. The 1,6- dienyne reductive radical cyclization is especially noteworthy for its regioselectivity (Scheme 8b). Under classical radical conditions, alcohol 65b selectively aﬀorded a jungermanne- none-type skeleton, and ketone 65a exclusively formed ent- kaurane. Other two-electron-based conditions (reductive coupling, reductive Heck, cycloisomerization, etc.) were found to be unsuccessful. The natural products 10 and 7 were successfully synthesized thereafter. Furthermore, radical Bar- ton−McCombie deoxygenation was introduced to deliver 9. Finally, a radical-based late-stage photoinduced skeletal rearrangement was found to be responsible for the inter- conversion between 7 and 72, which is distinct from nature’s enzymatic carbocationic pathway. All the other attempts employing two-electron-based transformations turned out to be unsuccessful. Overall, the application of radical-based transformations (Scheme 8, in orange) shows their unrivaled signiﬁcance in ent-kaurane total synthesis both tactically and strategically. Total Synthesis of ent-Kauradienone and Jungermannenones

The jungermannenones are new rearranged ent-kaurane isolated from the liverwort Jungermannia species, and they display promising cytotoxicity.37,39 From a synthetic point of view, jungermannenones present a formidable challenge due to their unique bicyclic[3,2,1]-octene framework possessing an endocy- clic tetrasubstituted alkene moiety. Our synthetic studies commenced with commercially available 6-heptyn-1-ol (73, Scheme 9a),4 and aldehyde 74 was readily available over three steps from 73. Enantioselective radical cation bicyclization of 74 upon organo-SOMO catalysis successfully generated desired aldehyde 76 in good yield and ee. Further three-step transformations (α-methylation, Wolﬀ− Kishner-Huang reduction and benzylic oxidation) followed by radical Birch reduction/acid hydrolysis cascade and α- propargylation aﬀorded dienyne 65a. Luche reduction of 65a yielded 65b. As mentioned above, classical radical chemistry (tri-n-butyltin hydride/AIBN) was proven to be the best condition for our reductive radical cyclization. ent-Kurane-type scaﬀold 67 with C8 cyclization was obtained exclusively from 65a after in situ destannylation. Likewise, radical cyclization occurred exclusively at the C11 position to give jungermanne- none-type scaﬀold 66 as the sole product from 65b. Starting from both 66 and 67, selective oxidative cleavage of the exocyclic double bond and installation of exoenone enabled the ﬁrst total synthesis of ent-kurandienone (10) and jungermanenone C (7) without any protecting group manipulations. The eﬃcient 1,6-dienyne reductive radical cyclization encouraged us in the scalable synthesis of rac-7 (Scheme 9b).3 Starting from the biosynthetic precursor geraniol 77, desired diene 79 was obtained over 2 steps on a 100 g scale. Subsequent intramolecular electrophilic hydroarylation of 79 using the protocol of Sames et al.40 furnished the known tricyclic intermediate rac-80. Afterward, the same approach provided scalable rac-7. Of note, 1,6-dienyne reductive cyclization could be operated on a 7.4 g scale without a signiﬁcant reduction in reaction yield. Finally, 1.6 g of rac-jungermannenone C was prepared, which is consequentially signiﬁcant for subsequent biological assessments. Finally, our total synthesis-driven biological investigation revealed ent-7 can act as an eﬀective diﬀerentiation therapy agent against AML (acute myeloid leukemia) as a covalent protein binder.31c The current 1,6-dienyne reductive radical cyclization is especially noteworthy for its scalability and substrate-dominated regioselectivity. The present regiochemistry of radical additions to the C8 and C11 positions has been investigated by density functional theory (DFT) calculations.3,4 The results show that the formation of ent-kaurane 67 is mainly controlled by geometry. Simultaneously, the formation of jungermannenone 66 is demonstrated to be favored both kinetically and thermodynamically. On the basis of our successful application of dienyne reductive radical cyclization, a sustained interest guided us in further exploration of this substrate-based cyclization. As a result, a

Such biomimetic enzyme-free carbocationic rearrangements have long been discussed in diterpenoid synthetic endeavors.33,34 Inspired by the carboca- tionic hypotheses and our successful diterpenoid syntheses, we began to explore the possibility of rearranging ent-kauranes to jungermannenones biomimetically.4 A model study with 86 was ﬁrst undertaken, yet no rearrangement was observed under a series of acidic, thermal, radical, and transition-metal-catalyzed reaction conditions. To our delight, UV irradiation was found to serve as the driving force for the equilibrium between 86 and 87. Such reactivity can be explained by two plausible mechanisms: a dissociation-recombination mechanism involv- ing a cage radical pair 88a or a quasi-concerted pathway involving a biradical “tight” intermediate 88b.42 To the best of our knowledge, no photochemical or radical rearrangement has been previously reported to be involved in the biosynthesis of Isodon diterpenoids. We envisaged that the aforementioned photoinduced skeletal rearrangement lies behind the late-stage assembly of the bicyclo[3.2.1]octene skeleton. First, the key proposed precursor 72 for photoinduced skeletal rearrangement was generated by selective Luche reduction of 10. Fortunately, ent-kaurane type 72 can be transformed into 7 under 254 nm UV light irradiation. ent- Kaurane type 72 was formed when 7 was treated with 365 nm UV light. Sunlight-promoted interconversion of ent-kaurane and jungermannenone further suggested that this photoinduced radical skeletal rearrangement may be involved in their biosynthetic pathway, which was previously hypothesized to involve carbocationic rearrangements. Ultimately, we success- fully performed late-stage photoinduced skeletal rearrangement with a series of diterpenoids (89−91), sesquiterpenoids (92, 93), or natural product analogues (94) bearing diverse functional groups (Scheme 10c). Total Synthesis of Jungermatrobrumin A The ent-kaurane-type diterpenoids possess remarkable struc- tural diversity, especially in terms of oxidative state and a myriad of biological activities. Total Synthesis of ent-Kauranes by a [3 + 2+1] Cycloaddition/Cycloalkenylation Approach The radical process in our synthesis of ent-kauranes is unprecedentedly eﬃcient at the late stage of synthesis, and multistep reactions are required to construct the tetracyclic skeleton. Innovation at the early stage of synthesis is inevitable for quick access to ent-kauranes. With 112 in hand, Barton−McCombie deoxygenation furnished the total synthesis of 12-oxo-9,11-dehydrokaurene (11). Further diastereoselective reduction under Luche reduction conditions delivered the reported structure of 12β-hydroxy-9,11-dehydro- kaurene 113. Subsequently, 12β-OH and 12α-OH were found to be in equilibrium under acidic conditions, and the structure of 113 was revised to 12α-hydroxy-12. Meanwhile, with 114 as the starting material, two-step transformations enabled the ﬁrst total synthesis of ent-1α-hydroxykauran-12-one (13). ■ TOTAL SYNTHESIS OF ALKALOIDS VIA A

Diversity-oriented synthesis (DOS), conceptualized in the early 2000s by Schreiber’s lab, has been proven to be a powerful approach for the discovery of novel biologically active molecules over the last two decades.46 One popular systematic approach for DOS is the three-phase build/couple/pair (B/C/P) strategy.46 In this strategy, diverse molecular libraries are generated via intramolecular functional group pairing reactions (the pair phase) using precursors bearing multiple functional groups that have been constructed by coupling building blocks (the couple phase) that are presynthesized in the build phase. Although DOS has been proven to be a successful strategy for the eﬃcient, simultaneous synthesis of structurally diverse natural product-like three-dimensional molecules, it has rarely been applied to natural product total synthesis in parallel with skeletal diversiﬁcation. Classically, there are three major strategies for accessing diverse natural products or analogues FUNCTIONAL GROUP PAIRING STRATEGY (Scheme 15a): divergent total synthesis (I), functional group diversiﬁcation (II), and skeletal diversiﬁcation (III) of natural product(s). Divergent total synthesis (I) is a popular approach for constructing several members of a family of natural products, but it is rarely utilized for further diversiﬁcation of a polycyclic scaﬀold, while functional group diversiﬁcation (II) and skeletal diversiﬁcation (III) are two widely used strategies to produce diverse molecules directly from readily available natural products. Accordingly, we decided to develop a novel approach using DOS for the simultaneous construction of both natural products and their analogues in 2014 using the Lycopodium alkaloid as a model.1

Typically, natural products have various functional groups that “pair” together in diﬀerent patterns (connecting via C−C, C−N, C−O, or other bonds). In our strategy, we ﬁrst identify these hidden functional group pairing patterns (FGPPs) in diverse natural products. For example, the Lycopodium alkaloid (+)-serratezomine A47a (14) contains three hidden FGPPs, a lactone (B-C), an amine (E-F), and an all-carbon quaternary center (●-D), while (−)-lycoposerramine-U47b (15) has an additional methylene unit to connect C4 with N (E-F), as well as two all-carbon quaternary centers (●-D, C-E). Similarly, (+)-8α-hydroxyfawcettimine47c (16) bears a hemiaminal (B- F), an α-substituted cycloketone (C-E), and an all-carbon quaternary center (●-D), and (−)-serratinine47d contains two quaternary centers (●-D, C-E, E-F). After disconnecting these pairing functional groups, we then simpliﬁed these complex natural products into a multifunctionalized precursor such as 116 containing a single six-membered ring bearing two side chains that can be assembled by a three-component Michael- aldol sequence using allyl magnesium bromide 117, enone 118, and aldehyde 119, followed by Dess−Martin oxidation in the functional pairing build/couple phase. Finally, a variety of reactions can be used to construct distinct natural products and natural-product-like scaﬀolds in parallel from the same precursor (Scheme 15). The early pair phase was completed by performing the intramolecular alkylation between the enol and iodide of 116 https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.accounts.0c00531 Acc. Chem. Res. With spirocyclic intermedi- ate 124 in hand, further pairing reactions were carried out. A tandem deprotection/retro-Claisen condensation aﬀorded γ- lactone 125, which was transformed into a 5/6/5 system 126 through tandem deprotection/transannular cyclization. Another pairing pathway between C and E generated α-hydroxyl ketone 129 via Lemieux−Johnson oxidation and subsequent intra- molecular benzoin reaction with Rovis’s NHC (N-heterocyclic carbene) precatalyst 128.48 Meanwhile, selective reduction of the carbonyl group at C13 in 124 followed by oxidative cleavage of the terminal alkene and Pinnick oxidation aﬀorded acid 130 in high yield. Next, a key one-pot ring-forming reaction in two pairings, B-C/E-F or A-C/E-F, was performed to construct the bridged δ-lactone or fused γ-lactone-based tetracyclic architec- ture. Remarkably, (+)-serratezomine A (14) was successfully obtained in 30% yield with its 4-epimer 132 in 19% yield and γ- lactone 120 in 15% yield when acid 130 was treated with triﬂuoroacetic anhydride followed by TFA and NaBH3CN.

Moreover, the intramolecular benzoin reaction was applied to pair B-C and C-E concurrently (Scheme 17). The key precursor 116 was converted into aldehyde 133 via Lemieux−Johnson oxidation, setting the stage for the key intramolecular benzoin reaction. After extensive screening of the conditions, 6/5/9 systems 135 and 134 were successfully produced in 51% and 42% isolated yields, respectively, when aldehyde 133 was subjected to NHC precatalyst 128 and triethylamine in chloroform at 55 °C. A subsequent one-pot deprotection/ transannular N-alkylation of 135 generated a 6/5/6/5 system 121, while a selective double reductive amination between 135 and methylamine hydrochloride successfully aﬀorded a 6/5/5/9 system 122. Meanwhile, α-ketol 134 could serve as a substrate for several other pairing reactions. Notably, SmI2 reduction of α-ketol 134 followed by a tandem deprotection/transannular Mannich reaction furnished (−)-Ly- coposerramine-U (15) in moderate yield, completing the E-F pairing. Removal of the Boc group in 134 with TFA produced carbinolamine at C5 exclusively, and subsequent TMS deprotection gave a 6/5/6/7 system 123. Furthermore, subjecting 134 to SOCl2 and Et3N led to the expected 6/5/6/ 5 system via an intramolecular SN2 reaction, constructing another E-F pairing. Advanced intermediate 136, which was obtained upon removal of the TMS group by in situ generated acid, served as an entry point into two Lycopodium alkaloids. Selective reduction of the carbonyl group at C13 in 136 furnished (−)-serratinine(17), while (+)-8α-hydroxyfawcetti- mine (16) was also generated from 136 via reductive cleavage of the C4−N bond, followed by carbinoamine formation using SmI2.49

Indole alkaloids are a large family of natural products that possess diverse structures and various bioactivities.50 In 2019, we accomplished the total syntheses of chaetoglines,51 which are the ﬁrst fungal indole alkaloid natural products, in a divergent and bioinspired manner via our FGPP strategy.52 Similarly, we envisioned that chaetoglines C−F can be derived from key intermediate 137 via functional group pairing reactions and functional group maneuvers. A high-yield, one-step condensa- tion of readily synthesized building blocks 142 and 143 can generate the pivotal intermediate 137 (Scheme 18). Our synthesis commenced with lactone 142, which can be easily obtained from acid 144 via a known procedure followed by protection group manipulation. Aminolysis of lactone 142 followed by oxidation and hydrolysis eﬃciently aﬀorded hemiacetal 145. Subsequent condensation between 145 and N-methyltryptophan methyl ester 143 proceeded smoothly with the treatment of excess triethylamine, yielding hemiaminal 137, which served as a key intermediate for the synthesis of chaetoglines. After extensively screening diﬀerent Bronsted acids and Lewis acids, we found that, upon treatment of 137 with TMSOTf at 0 °C, the stereoselective Pictet−Spengler (PS) reaction occurred eﬃciently to give 146 in 65% isolated yield, completing the A-C pair. Hydrolysis of the methyl ester followed by global deprotection provided chaetogline E (139) in good yield. Removal of the extra carboxyl group via the Barton decarboxylation reaction smoothly aﬀorded compound 148. The synthesis of chaetogline F (138) was ﬁnally accomplished via three-step transformation (oxidative aromatization, methyl- ation, deprotection). In this Account, we provide insight into our endeavors in the total syntheses for a variety of structurally diverse polycyclic natural products by using newly developed synthetic strategies including sequential C−H functionalizations, or concepts, radical transformations, and functional group pairing pattern recognition. These approaches enable straightforward access to natural products and their analogues for subsequent chemical biology studies to generate potential lead compounds for drug discovery.
